Qtamp licensing and provenance
==============================

This document explains the licensing situation around Qtamp as a
project, what is in this repository and how it is licensed, and what
you need to fetch yourself in order to build it.


Code in this repository
-----------------------

Qtamp's git history begins as a rewrite of the Qt-native Winamp port
formerly hosted at https://github.com/lord3nd3r/winamp-linux. Every
path that originated from the Llama Group's 2024 Winamp open-source
release (the upstream `Src/`, `lang/`, `Qt/`, `BuildTools/`,
`packaging/`, the `LICENSE.md` containing the Winamp Collaborative
License, and a number of Win32-specific build files) was removed from
every commit before publication. None of those files exist in this
repository's working tree, packed objects, or pack indexes.

What remains in the imported history is the Qt-native port code
authored by 3nd3r (lord3nd3r) — primarily the contents of `src/`,
the root `CMakeLists.txt`, `build_linux.sh`, `README_LINUX.md`, and
the `.github/` CI workflow. 3nd3r has explicitly granted permission
to relicense those contributions under the MIT License for inclusion
in Qtamp; see `LICENSES/lord3nd3r/MIT`.

Everything else in this repository is original work authored by
Qtamp contributors under the MIT License; see
`LICENSES/preferred/MIT`.

Therefore every file you find in this repository is MIT-licensed.


Code that is NOT in this repository
-----------------------------------

Qtamp is the reference embedder for qtWasabi (the open-source
continuation of the Wasabi/Maki skin engine that Winamp shipped).
Qtamp links against qtWasabi at build time. qtWasabi in turn embeds
the Maki bytecode VM and a small portable subset of Wasabi's
foundation classes (BFC) from the official 2024 Llama Group Winamp
open-source release. None of that source lives here.

To build Qtamp end-to-end:

  1. Run scripts/fetch-deps.sh. The script clones qtWasabi into
     deps/qtWasabi (gitignored) and invokes qtWasabi's own
     scripts/fetch-wasabi.sh to download the Llama Group release
     into deps/qtWasabi/wasabi-src/ (also gitignored).
  2. The build links qtWasabi (MIT) into the Qtamp binary on your
     local machine. qtWasabi in turn statically pulls in the
     Maki VM and BFC subset from your local Wasabi source tree.
  3. The license governing the linked-in Winamp pieces is whichever
     license the Llama Group ships with the official source release.
     Read the LICENSE.md file inside that release for the exact
     terms. Honouring those terms is your responsibility as the
     person doing the build.

This is the same model qtWasabi uses, and the same model console
emulators use for BIOS files: the framework code is freely
distributable under its own license, the machine-specific files
come from the user.


Third-party libraries linked at runtime
---------------------------------------

  qtWasabi          MIT, fetched at build time, see
                    https://github.com/qtWasabi/qtWasabi
  Qt 6              dual-licensed LGPLv3 / commercial; Qtamp links
                    dynamically under the LGPLv3 terms
  FluidSynth        LGPL-2.1-or-later; Qtamp links dynamically for
                    MIDI playback (in_midi plugin)
  RtMidi            MIT; Qtamp links dynamically for MIDI controller
                    input
  FFmpeg            (via Qt 6.5+ Multimedia) LGPL-2.1+; Qtamp links
                    dynamically for the in_ffmpeg input plugin

None of these libraries ship as source in this repository. All are
fetched by the system package manager, by Qt's own bundling, or by
scripts/fetch-deps.sh.


Summary
-------

  Qtamp (this repository)
      MIT, see LICENSES/preferred/MIT and LICENSES/lord3nd3r/MIT.

  qtWasabi
      MIT, fetched into deps/qtWasabi at build time.

  Maki VM and BFC subset
      Official Winamp open-source release, fetched at build time
      via qtWasabi's scripts/fetch-wasabi.sh, governed by the
      license shipped with that release.

  No Winamp or Wasabi source in this repository or its git history.
